    <abstract>
        <para>
            Remove the angle (in radians) value from the stack, and push the sine of the angle.
        </para>
        <para>
            The data type expected by <command>math.sin</command> is determined by the last
            <command>with<emphasis>&lt;type&gt;</emphasis></command> instruction. The valid options for
            <command>math.sin</command> are: <olink targetptr="asm_withfloat">withfloat</olink> and
            <olink targetptr="asm_withdouble">withdouble</olink>.
        </para>
        <para>
            An alternative to explicitly calling one of the <command>with<emphasis>&lt;type&gt;</emphasis></command>
            instructions before calling <command>math.sin</command> is to use one of the prefixed versions of the the
            instruction, namely:
        </para>
        <para>
            <command>math.fsin</command> or <command>math.dsin</command>
        </para>
        <para>
            The assembler will expand these to a corresponding <command>with<emphasis>&lt;type&gt;</emphasis></command>
            instruction followed by <command>math.sin</command>.
        </para>
    </abstract>
    <sect2>
        <title>Synopsis</title>
        <funcsynopsis>
            <para><emphasis role="args">angle</emphasis></para>
            <para><command>math.sin</command></para>
        </funcsynopsis>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
        <title>Arguments</title>
        <itemizedlist>
            <para><emphasis role="args">&lt;angle&gt;</emphasis> - the angle (in radians) to find the sine of</para>
        </itemizedlist>
        <note><para>This synopsis shows an immediate value being explicitly placed onto the stack.
            However, the value could be the result peripheral I/O, function calls or any number of mathematical
            expressions. Or it could be an arbitrary combination of all of these.</para></note>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
        <title>Returns</title>
        <para>
            Returns the sine of the given angle.
        </para>
    </sect2>
